04702nam a22006375i 9780520974487DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20212021cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020034104  a97805209744877 a10.1525/97805209744872doi  a(DE-B1597)551592  a(OCoLC)1191456794  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHD7304.D6bH47 2021 4aHD7304.D6 7aSOC0260302bisacsh04a330.9774/342231 aHerbert, Claire W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Detroit Story :bUrban Decline and the Rise of Property Informality /cClaire W. Herbert. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (316 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations and Tables -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Social and Spatial Context -- t1. Urban Decline and Informality -- t2. Regulations and Enforcement -- t3. From Illicit to Informal -- tPart II. Informality in Everyday Life -- t4. Beyond Politics or Poverty -- t5. Necessity Appropriators -- t6. Lifestyle Appropriators -- t7. Routine Appropriators -- tPart III. Informal Plans and Formal Policies -- t8. Surviving the City or Settling the City? -- t9. Regulating Informality, Reproducing Inequality -- tConclusion: Lessons for Informality in the Global North -- tAppendix: Research Methods and Data -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBringing to the fore a wealth of original research, A Detroit Story examines how the reclamation of abandoned property has been shaping the city for decades. Herbert lived in Detroit for almost five years to get a ground-view sense of how this process molds urban areas—participating in community meetings and tax foreclosure protests, interviewing various groups, following scrappers through abandoned buildings, and visiting squatted houses and gardens. Herbert found that there’s a disjunction between different types of property reclaimers: lifestyle back-to-the-earth new residents, primarily more privileged, whose practices are often formalized by local policies, and longtime more disempowered residents, often representing communities of color, whose practices are marked as illegal and illegitimate. She teases out how the divergent treatment of these two approaches to informally claiming property reproduces long-standing inequalities in race, class, and property ownership. More generally, A Detroit Story examines how the attempt to formalize property informality in cities harms the most vulnerable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aGentrificationzMichiganzDetroit. 0aHousingxAbandonmentzMichiganzDetroit. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073915240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520974487zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520974487423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520974487/original  a978-3-11-073915-2  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075418-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishb2021  